<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFB7FFED6DC2FA93FEFCAE63" pageId="19" pageNumber="1532" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFB7FFED6DC2FA93FEFCAE63" blockId="19.[178,1085,1294,1377]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1532">
Etymology: The specific epithet 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB7FFED6F3EFA93FD5BAE21" box="[590,718,1294,1315]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1532">undulicornis</emphasis>
is a Latin compound name derived from 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB7FFED6D9BFAB0FE8BAE40" box="[235,286,1325,1346]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1532">unda</emphasis>
(= wave) and 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB7FFED6CC6FAB0FE64AE40" box="[438,497,1325,1346]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1532">cornu</emphasis>
(= horn). I refer to the undulation of the anterior margin of antennomere 9.
</paragraph>
